title: For Sale/Trade:  Modelo Mauser in Great Condition and Sporterized!
postcontent:
I am selling a Modelo Mauser with a crest saying "FAPR'CA NACIONAL DE ARMAS - MEXICO D.F." and stamped 1933. This particular rifle has been re-chambered in 7.62 x 39 (AK Round). The only downsides are that the rifle needs to be chambered with enough force otherwise the round will not catch on the extractor and will lead to a misfire (because the pin will miss the primer) and it will not securely hold more than one or two rounds in the magazine due to the small size of this round (Which isn't a big deal IMO as it is a bolt action and I only loaded one round at a time anyway). Otherwise, the conversion is really nice as you can shoot cheap and commonly found 7.62x39. This conversion was not done by me, but the previous owner's father who passed last year. 

The rifle has a very nice Walnut Stock with a great finish, a very crisp trigger, stainless steel bolt and magazine follower, a white dotted front sight with hood, an aftermarket William's Rear Sight adjustable for Wind. and Elev. and the rifle comes with a brown and tan leather case which has been with the rifle for as long as I can remember. All I can say is that it is a fun shooter, holds a lot of character and of course uses the tried and true German Mauser action with the complete 3 point safety.

postcontent:
Seiko Auto-Relay Kinetic Watch with a Titanium body & band. The Kinetic feature basically charges the watch every time you move while wearing it. So instead of relying on changing out a battery every few years, it constantly charges with being worn.

The Auto-Relay feature basically will completely stop the watch after I think 2-3 days of inactivity to quit using the battery. After you shake the watch, it will automatically go to the correct time. You will usually have to reset the calender feature.

I wore it for basically a year, and its been sitting in my dresser drawer for years. So while it is a ultra nice watch, I really don't need it. It has the presentation box, and I'm nearly sure with paperwork as well.

If you held the Generation I & II vests side by side, it might be hard to tell the difference. For operators in the field, however, even a set of subtle changes can have far-reaching effects. 
The Improved Outer Tactical Vest (IOTV) incorporates new utility features and design enhancements which provide lightweight comfort and maximum protection. All of IOTV’s improvements result in a fully integrated vest that not only offers the most advanced protection available but greater maneuverability for mission effectiveness.

•	One change set involved expanding vertical adjustment of the side plate carriers, and allowing horizontal changes. This allows IOTV to properly fit a wider variety of soldier sizes, including women.
•	The Gen II design converted back to Cordura for mesh, because the previous material was so “aggressive” that it was damaging the uniform underneath. 
•	Streamlining the quick release cable handle to reduce pinch-points or friction, so it can weigh less and work better.
•	More than three pounds lighter than OTV
•	Lower back extender protects the lower spine region and increases the vest’s coverage by 52 square inches
•	Internal waistband enhances mobility by distributing the weight from the shoulders to the waist and helps stabilize the load

Each box contains 10 plastic plugged tubes with 10 cartridges in each tubes for a total of 100 rounds. These bullets have no cartridge case as well as no primer to cause rust and corrosion. The V-L bullet consists merely of a cylindrical plug of solid propellant attached to the rear of a slug or missile. When the trigger of a V-L rifle is pulled, a powerful spring drives a cocked plunger into a cylinder, compressing and heating the trapped air to about 2,000° F. Escaping into the firing chamber through a valve, a jet of heated air strikes and ignites the propellant, which pushes the missile through the barrel

title: For Sale/Trade:  1989 Ford Bronco II (Eddie Bauer)
postcontent:
I will be relocating very soon, so this needs to go. Owned by my grandfather since the mid-1990s, until his passing. Owned by me since last summer. This is one of the good Bronco II's, and there are fewer and fewer good ones hanging around. Way too nice to junk, even with its problems (see below). Read the whole ad before responding, please.

1989 Ford Bronco II (Eddie Bauer)
 Mileage: 152k
 Engine: Fuel Injected 2.9L V6
 Tires: Kelley Safari (lots of tread)

THE GOOD:
 -Strong, smooth engine that starts up like a champ.
 -Push button 4x4 works (sometimes have to push the button a couple of times). Old-school, constant power to all four wheels. Makes for fun snow driving.
 -Nicest interior you'll find in a Bronco II. Just a little wear on the edge of the driver's seat, and it isn't much. Rear of the interior looks new.
 -Power locks/windows work (sometimes finicky)
 -I trusted this car all winter, and it got me and the kids everywhere with no problem. 
-Looks good. This one could easily be turned into a real head turner.
 -Is a daily driver in the winter, and I make sure to take a small trip in it once a week or so in the summer.

THE BAD:
 -Transmission will need work soon. Started slipping this spring. Beyond my mechanical ability, so I don't know if it is a 'fix' or a 'replace' situation. I am pricing the truck as if it needs the transmission replaced.
 -Valve cover needs tightened or gasket replaced. Have driven truck 3,000 miles without having to add oil, so it's very minor. I never felt the need to mess with it.
 -Has rust. The bad rust is the bottom of the driver's side. Frame is strong and not rusted out. Pictures are from last fall, and the rust has taken just a bit more of the driver's side door since the pictures were taken. Exterior still far above average for a Bronco II.
 -AC needs charged and radio doesn't work for some unknown reason.
 -Rear liftgate struts are old, so the back hatch doesn't hold itself up very well unless it's hot outside.

I hate to let my Bronco II go, but I am rushing around to relocate for a new job, and I am not going to have the time, space or money to spend messing with it. Clear title in hand (just renewed tags last week, just my luck). I know what junkyard prices are, and the wheels/tires on this one would be easy to sell seperately. The truck, particularly the transmission, needing an unknown amount work is the only reason this truck is priced this low. I would be fixing it myself if I didn't have to move suddenly.

ASKING $850. Open to 'certain types' of trades.

Once again, the pictures are almost a year old, and the rust is a little worse than the pictures show.  Still a very good looking little Bronco II.

title: For Sale:  WTS Springfield 1903 A3 Remington Camp Perry Match
postcontent:
Springfield 1903 A3 Remington in near perfect condition, that has been set up for Camp Perry matches with Redfield target peep sights. The sights themselves are in perfect condition with no wear present. 

The bore is in pristine condition, extremely shiny with a small amount of powder fouling present and no corrosion. The 2 groove rifling is perfect with sharp edges, and the grooves show no buildup where they meet the rifling. The barrel is practically brand new. 

The action is also much smoother than my other two Springfields, and may or may not have been worked on. The trigger is extremely smooth and light with absolutely no creep, and a light and clean break, that again may or may not have had work done to it. 

The parkerizing on the firearm is in perfect shape no fading or noticable wear except for a couple of small scrapes at the end of the barrel. The bluing on the bolt is a perfect black worn only from operating the action. The bolt face is the same. The peripheral parts, such as the barrel bands, floor plate, and end cap exhibit a little more wear. The barrel bands still retain most of their bluing with some combat scrapes present. The floor plate has virtually no finish left and could be polished. The end cap retains most of the blueing with some wear present. The buttplate also has most of the blue still intact, although not shiny. There is also a small amount of older corrosion present that appears inactive. The follower in the fixed magazine appears to have been polished. 

The stock is near perfect with some white flecks on the left side. The only small dings are in the bottom of the buttstock where the plate meets the wood, and behind the trigger guard. The worst wear is in front of the first barrel band where it appears someone did not loosen it before taking it off. This also seems to be an older scrape as it has smoothed over from handling and looks much worse in the picture than in reality. Overall the rifle is in exceptional condition and match ready. 

Ships to C and R or FFL only, from C and R. Feel free to ask any questions.
